review_blob: Pours a dark maroonish brown with a thick, micro-bubble, golden-brown head. Exquisitely rich aroma of bittersweet dark chocolate, espresso, toffee, and wine. Immediately stands out from any other stout of this caliber. A very unique sweetness reminiscent of sugary raisins, before it settles into more classic coffee and roasted malt flavors. Not the stand out Belgian yeast flavor I had expected, this is such a full bodied stout that it blends right in with the rest of the flavors. A hint of smoke and chocolate milk really round out the heavy flavors balanced by a nice hop presence. A beer that would be intriguing over and over again.

Pours a dark golden honey amber with a small off-white head. Delicious aroma of sticky honey malts and caramelized piney hops. Very full bodied creamy texture. The malts are very powerful up front: sticky, honey and bready flavors. The hops on the end arent as powerful as the 90 minute. They provide a less bitter, but smooth transition from the sticky malts to a refreshing honey citrus finish. A unique IPA.

Pours an incredible fudge brown with a thick and creamy chocolate head. Absolutely beautiful. The aroma is a perfect blend of sweet coffee roast and chocolate earthiness. The mouthfeel is exquisitely smooth and full, with just a hint of carbonation. The flavor is full of the delicious coffee all the way through. Some chocolate, buttery flavors also show through in the beginning, and it finishes very mellow and slightly bitter sweet.

Pours a hazy golden yellow with a fizzy white head. Sweet, bready aromas of pineapple and yeast. The flavor is very full and represents the wheat category well. The sweet orange and pineapple fruitiness compliments the bready yeast flavors very well. The body is full from the wheat but has a nice carbonation. Delicious and refreshing beer.

Pours a dark, slightly hazy amber with a huge tan head. Very interesting aroma. Both the American hops and the Belgian yeast are both very prevalent. The bready and citrus aromas play well on each other. The flavor is extremely dry. The bready yeast flavors dominate this beer. Some slight orangey sweetness shows up at first from the hops, but the finish is short and doesnt leave much.

Pours a very dark brown with a small off-white head. Great aroma with a mix of sweet coffees, lightly roasted caramel malts, and sweet nectar hops. The flavors dont mesh quite as well as the aromas. There is a light earthiness from the roasted malts, but the overriding flavor is a slightly bitter citrus hops. The black malt character is an interesting play on the bitter hops, but Im not sure I get it.

Pours a hazy orange amber with a dense off-white head. Incredible sugary sweet honey, orange marmalade and pine aroma of the simcoe hops. The sweetness is more subtle in the early flavors of the beer. The hops really dominate with a woody bitterness. The body is very full and creamy with some other honey like flavors too.

Pours a hazy gold with a huge white head. Highly carbonated beer. You can smell the spritzy carbonation in with some sharp, tart citrus, sweet breads, and Belgian yeast. Very dry flavor. The citrus and bread make a very robust tart, grassy flavor. The finish is very dry alcohol, and the overall body is very carbonated and herbal.

Pours a clear, medium gold with a tall, foamy white head. Corny malt aroma of  grain and light citrus. The body is very smooth, with that grainy malt character giving most of the flavor, with some herbal, grassy notes towards the end. Very refreshing. Good Pilsner.
beer_name: Oskar Blues Mamas Little Yella Pils

review_blob: Pours a clear golden amber with a small white head. Very grainy, bready Belgian aroma with a couple other spices and some malt scents coming up too. Flavor is really all over the place (as expected i guess). The rice takes me back too much towards those macros, but some of the flavors are pretty good. The Belgian yeast is the most notable in its bready and tart contribution, but the ginger adds a unique twist, and the overall impression is fairly sweet. Very interesting and fun beer. Keep in mind the concept, bringing the world together (one beer at a time)!

Pours a reddish amber with a small beige head. Week aroma, I  can hardly smell the malts and there is no sign of much else. Very full and creamy body though. This beer has a nice caramel nutty flavor thats very smooth. Its malt heavy as expected, but pretty pleasant overall. The rich maple sugary flavors really carry this one through. Underrated in my opinion.

Pours a dark fudge brown with a tall brown head. The aroma is strong sweet chocolate with some smooth coffee and light roastiness. Very creamy mouth feel. The flavor is very strong coffee with some woody roastiness. Theres also some sweet chocolaty flavors.  The bitterness from the cofee and the warming of the alcohol combine in the finish.
beer_name: Great Divide Yeti Imperial Stout - Espresso Oak Aged

review_blob: Pours a beautiful orange, amber with a small off-white head. Wonderful light honey, citrus, hops, and sweet mellow woods. Incredibly unique flavor. Very sweet nectar and honey upfront with some melon flavors. The sweetness blends right into the bitter hop finish. The hop resins fold into the background oak to leave a really amazing sweet finish. Delicious.

Pours a very dark oily brown with a small light brown head. Very sweet almost fruity fudge aroma, The caramel, lightly roasted malts really dominate the smell. Wow, very sweet flavor for an Imperial Stout too. Molasses, chocolate flavors with very minimal roastiness. Pretty tasty. Nice smooth mouthfeel, maybe a little oily.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Imperial Series Imperial Stout

review_blob: Pours a hazy, honey/orange with a small white head. Great sweet hop aroma with scents of honey, orange and other sweet citrus. The flavor is very fruity upfront with some light honey. The finish is bitter but very smooth with a great flowery hop flavor. Very well balanced beer with a lot of flavorful character and a great, smooth creamy mouthfeel.
beer_name: Rogue Nation Brutal India Pale Ale

review_blob: 2005 bottle: Pours a very red brown with a small white head. Very strange aroma. Super tart with a few sweet cherries and wet wood smells. What a unique flavor. A little spritzy with a light sweetness and a sour tartness that dominates the flavor and puckers the mouth. Sweet cherries fill in the body a little, but the dry wood and tart citrus make up the  majority of the flavor.

Pours a dark rusty brown with a tall beige head. Delicious caramel, with nuts, bready Belginan yeast and some very ripe citrus fruits in the aroma. Very delicious flavor as well. Some over-ripe fruits, nuts, and spices combine very well with the sweet caramel malts to form a very nice balance. The creamy texture really slides down and hides the alcohol well. Great beer with a lot of the best parts of the Belgian styles.

Pours a slightly hazy amber gold with a small off-white head. Great sweet honey aroma. Lots of floral, herbal, and piney hop smells. Very sweet honey malt flavor up-front, but totally dominated by the bitter, grassy, pine hop finish. Very delicious although hop heavy. It lingers with a grassy, dry flavor. Very distinct California IPA character.

Pours a dark copper with a decent beige head. Mildly sweet caramel aroma with a little grassiness. Strong sweet grape flavor initially that turns plumish with a heavy, sweet, malt and a more roasted earthy character later on. Very smooth and dignified. Very deep palate with a little dry feeling on the finish.

Pours a ruby amber with a small off-white head. Very nice aroma of caramel malts, brown sugar, toffee, and alcohol. Tastes like a fine cognac at room temperature with a huge caramel base and some strong candy sugary sweetness. Almost no hops. The heat of the alcohol lingers and swells with a diminishing sweetness on the tongue. A pleasure.

beer_brewer_name: Brouwerij der Trappistenabdij De Achelse Kluis
review_blob: Pours a hazy copper brown with a lot of sediment and a huge tan head. Interesting aroma of light yeast and fruit. Flavor is sweet malt all around, but dominated by cherries later on. Only a little bready Belgian yeast. Very fruity and sweet with a lasting finish of fruit and grain.

Pours a dark copper red with a small beige head. Peaty aroma of slightly roasted caramel and oak. Flavor is instant scotch. Very woody with sweet caramel notes and a little charred flavor. The finish is mildly sweet and sticky.
beer_name: Three Floyds Robert The Bruce Scottish Ale

review_blob: Pours a dark honey amber with a small off-white head. Fantastic deep, nutty, caramel malt aroma for a pale ale. Also smells of sweet American hops. Flavor is great. Extremely smooth and balanced between the honey nectar of the malts and the flowery bitter hops on the end. A few nutty flavors too. Incredible pale ale, a step over Stones and Dales.

Pours a clear honey gold with a medium off-white head. Pretty nice pale ale aroma. Some mild caramel sweetness with a leafy hop smell overriding. Flavor is very bland. Clearly an attempt at an acceptable pale ale rather then a great pale ale. Could have taken a note from Dales Pale on how to be both. Overall its pretty smooth, but brings some off flavors to the table.

Pours a clear, dark copper red with a medium beige head. Big sweet aroma of honey, brown sugar, and sweet malts along with some Cascade hops. Flavor is very sweet upfront with a nectar like honey and sugar flavor. But the bitter hops do come through to balance in the finish. I think the fact that it wasnt fully fermented to Gnarleywine leaves it a little sweet and sticky, but its still a very tasty barley wine. Maybe a little too grassy at the end.

Pours a hazy ruby copper with very little tan head. Delicious, sticky sweet aroma of cider, caramel, toffee, and sourdough. Taste is also an extreme malt presence. The caramel, toffee, and raisin flavors come out strong at first with a dry but smooth finish. Not much hop anything in this brew, but the finish does linger with a little earthiness. Big beer but very delicious.

Pours a clear, ruby red with a tall light brown head. Aroma of grain and citrus. The Belgian breadyness is subdued in the smell. Very caramel, nutty sweetness at first, followed by a semisweet bready finish that lingers with a funky quality. Very full, creamy body. Nailed the flavor.

Pours a ruby, brown, copper with a small beige head. Aroma is very sweet and sticky with lots of herbal notes. Aroma reflects in the flavor of fresh brewed tea. Some sweet berries and grassy hops finish off the brew. Some roasty notes as well, very unique brew.
beer_name: Stone / Jolly Pumpkin / Ngne  Special Holiday Ale

review_blob: Pours a clear orange/amber with a thick off-white head. Incredibly sweet aroma of honey and nectar! It just makes my mouth water from a mile away! Lots of sugary strawberry smells. The taste is equally wonderful sweet honey followed by a dry, bitter hop finish. The citrus/piney hop flavor leaves a fantastic sweet finish that lingers forever... so so good.
Pours a dark brown with a ruby undertone. Very roasty espresso and earthy aromas. Flavor is also a roasty espresso with some smokey, earthy notes. Pretty light body with a dry finish.
Pours a clear red,, copper with a small beige head. Light aroma of caramel thats a little roasted. Flavor is also mildly sweet with a little caramel, a little oak, and a slightly smokey finish.

Pours a mostly clear dark amber with a beige head. Aroma of slightly roasty caramel malts. Body is very light with the sweet caramel, slightly oaky malts running the show. Little nutty character too as it slides to a finish.

Pours a light gold with a small white head. Light aroma of slightly orange hops. The flavor has a unique orange and cherry like character with a less noticeable piney hops. Not very bitter and leaves a little grassy flavor with the finish.

Pours a slightly hazy orange color with a sticky white head. Smells a little muddled between sweet malts and woody hops. Extremely soft, smooth body with a lot of hop character, giving a woody, pine flavor with a slightly bitter finish.

Pours a darker honey with a foamy off-white head. Slightly sweet and citrusy aroma of Cascade hops. Very hop heavy flavor. You can feel the hop oils in your mouth. Lends to a creamy, mild malt base. Very smooth and only slightly bitter.
Pours a honey amber with a frothy white head. Aroma is very week. Flavor is a little nutty with some nice grassy caramel character. The hops show with a little dryness at the end. Decent Pale Ale.
Pours a nearly clear yellow with a bubbly white head. Nearly no aroma, maybe a little grainy. Bland flavor with no discernible malt character. Limited hops but at least smooth drinking.

2007 bottle: Pours a jet black with a small, light brown head. Amazingly deep aroma of fudge, raisins, light roastiness, and extremely heavy malts. Very similar malt character to the 120 IPA except for the darkness. Wow, this beer impresses me every time. So amazingly sweet. Flavors of raisins, sweet candied plums, and chocolate. Very light on the roasted coffee for a stout. I love this beer. The body is so smooth all the way through the finish and there is no hint of the high ABV. Delicious.

Pours a hazy reddish amber with a very small off-white head. Interesting aroma with an obvious hop presence but really dominated by the very heavy sweetness of the caramel malts. I can almost smell the grains seeping out. Flavor is absolutely delicious, and the body is very heavy. Very sweet, almost corn syrup like at first. With a smooth hop body that has no distinct beginning or end. Does an incredible job of hiding the extremely high ABV. Definitely an American Strong Ale as compared to the 90 minute.

Pours a crystal clear, honey amber with a small light tan head. Wonderful, mouth watering honey, and pine hop aroma. Perfect balance is the first thing I notice. Excellent sweet malt character up front with a light, maple honey flavor and a perfectly smooth hop profile. Leaves just a slightly bitter but still sweet lingering aftertaste. The body is light and silky. This stuff just slides down like candy.

Tap: Pours a dark brown with a decent tan head that fades completely. Pretty strong aroma of banana, lightly roasted nuts, and sweet caramel. Flavor does a good job of matching the banana nut bread flavor, but lacks any significant body. Comes off a little watery, but a very unique flavor. The finish is a little bland, but glad I tried it.

Pours a slightly hazy amber brown with a massive tan head. Extremely dry and spicy aroma with scents of bready Belgian yeast and herbal hops. Very dry flavor as well. Tonic, flavored water flavor with some hops and yeast lingering with the finish. Very diluted grape flavor. Unlike anything Ive ever tasted and not in a good way. Seems to be a bad bottle somehow.

Pours a clear amber with a medium, frothy beige head. Alcoholic citrus aroma with bready hints of Belgian yeast and cinnamon.  Bland and clashing flavors of spices, alcohol, light hops, and caramel. Very full bodied, just not a great flavor. The alcohol almost numbs the mouth afterwards.

Pours a dark chocolate brown with a short, light brown head. Great aroma of chocolate and slightly roasted caramel. Very chocolaty flavor with a creamy mouth feel and sweet, roasty notes. Sort of spicy as well with a mild, dry finish. Very dessert-like.

Pours a maple syrup red with a small off-white head. Wonderful sweet caramel aroma with a wealth of spices and light pine hops. Very full flavor and mouth feel. The sweet caramel is well complimented by an oaky undertone, and a smooth, spicy hop finish rounds out a wonderfully balanced beer. No hint of the ABV except a pleasant warming in the stomach. Excellent!

Pours a dark chocolaty brown with a medium brown head. Very pleasant chocolate and slightly roasted malt aroma. Delicious sweet caramel and bitter-sweet milk chocolate flavors at first. The body is creamy and smooth and the finish is a slightly roasted oak that fades nicely.

Pours a slightly hazy gold with a tall, foamy white head. Slightly sweet lemony aroma with a slightly bready quality. The flavor is also a little sweet and citrusy with a light caramel flavor at first and an almost negligible hop finish. Easy to drink summer beer though.

Pours an orange amber witha short white head. Amazing aroma of grape jelly and raisins. Very spritzy, highly carbonated mouth-feel. The flavor is semi sweet plum or grape jelly with a classic bready Belgian body. Lots of layered spices in the flavor as well. No hints of the ABV. Very smooth winter brew.

Pours a very dark brown, ruby with a lasting tan head. Sweet, malty, caramel corn aroma along with hints of vanillas and spices. The sweet flavors come out at first, but the body is too thin to hold the flavor. Turns a little dry towards the finish but leaves a nice candy sweetness as it fades. Slightly roasty caramel dominates the flavor.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2005 and later)

review_blob: Pours a clear red/amber with a small white head. Nice sweet citrus, and honey hop aroma. Flavor is also sweet caramel and citrus turning into a slightly bitter hop flavor. Very smooth with few harsh flavors.
